## 8. INCIDENT MANAGEMENT & POST-MORTEMS

### Standard: Formal process for detecting, responding, and learning from incidents

**Incident Severity Levels:**
```
Critical (P1):
├── Complete service outage
├── Data loss or security breach
├── All customers affected
└── SLA: Respond in 15 min, resolve in 4 hours

High (P2):
├── Partial service degradation
├── Some customers affected
├── Workaround available
└── SLA: Respond in 1 hour, resolve in 8 hours

Medium (P3):
├── Minor functionality issue
├── Single user or subset affected
├── No workaround required
└── SLA: Respond in 4 hours, resolve in 24 hours

Low (P4):
├── Cosmetic issues
├── No business impact
└── SLA: Respond in 24 hours
```

**Incident Response Workflow:**
```
1. Detection & Alerting
   ├── Alert triggered (monitoring)
   └── Acknowledged by on-call engineer

2. Initial Response
   ├── Severity assessed
   ├── On-call team assembled
   ├── War room/Slack channel created
   └── Customers notified (if high severity)

3. Investigation & Mitigation
   ├── Logs analyzed
   ├── Metrics reviewed
   ├── Hypothesis developed
   ├── Root cause identified
   └── Temporary fix/workaround deployed

4. Resolution
   ├── Permanent fix implemented
   ├── Testing completed
   ├── Deployment to production
   ├── Monitoring verified
   └── Status updates cease

5. Post-Incident Review (24 hours after)
   ├── Timeline documented
   ├── Root cause analysis (5 Whys)
   ├── Contributing factors identified
   ├── Action items for prevention
   ├── Lessons learned documented
   └── Report published & shared

Post-Mortem Template:
─────────────────────
Incident ID: INC-2026-001
Date & Time: 2026-04-15 14:00-16:30 UTC
Duration: 2 hours 30 minutes
Severity: High
Status: Resolved + Reviewed

Timeline:
14:00 - Alert: Database CPU > 80%
14:05 - On-call engineer paged
14:10 - Investigation started
14:35 - Root cause identified: Missing index
14:50 - Fix deployed to staging
15:00 - Fix deployed to production
15:30 - Monitoring confirmed healthy

Root Cause:
Missing index on client_id column in invoices table
Query plan: Full table scan (150M rows)
Performance: 0.5s → 45s query time

Contributing Factors:
- Index strategy not documented
- Code review didn't catch N+1 pattern
- No query performance monitoring alerting

Impact:
- 500+ customers affected
- 2.5 hours downtime
- Estimated $50k revenue impact

Timeline (Detailed):
- 14:00: Alert triggered (CPU > 80%)
- 14:03: Engineering team paged
- 14:10: On-call engineer logs in
- 14:15: Identifies slow query in logs
- 14:25: Traces to missing index
- 14:35: Creates index
- 14:50: Verifies fix in staging, deploys
- 15:00: Monitors production metrics

Action Items (Prevention):
1. Add missing indexes (3 items) - Owner: DBA - Due: 2026-04-17
2. Implement query monitoring - Owner: Backend Lead - Due: 2026-04-24
3. Database review checklist for PRs - Owner: Tech Lead - Due: 2026-04-20
4. Document index strategy - Owner: Architect - Due: 2026-04-22

Lessons Learned:
- Monitoring was insufficient for database query performance
- Index strategy not documented
- Code review should catch N+1 patterns
- Need for database load testing before production

Follow-up Actions:
☐ Implement action items by due dates
☐ Update index strategy documentation
☐ Add database load testing to CI/CD
☐ Share learning in team meeting
☐ Update postmortem procedure based on feedback
─────────────────────
```

